<DOCNO> AP890407-0001 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
there is no freedom without 
solidarity was the slogan shouted at countless rallies and 
marches since the east blocs first independent trade union was 
crushed by martial law in 1981 
but now that the union has lived through seven years of 
jailings beatings and even killings to win back its right to 
exist what will solidarity become 
many of the 10 million men and women who were active in the 
solidarity opposition movement of 198081 have emigrated or gone on 
to other activities 
some of its leaders have fallen away from the movement in 
disputes with chairman lech walesa 
a new generation of workers angry at shortages low wages and 
long waits for apartments has come to the fore many dont 
remember the solidarity of 198081 and have only a vague notion of 
what they want it to become 
but a core of activists behind walesa never let the flame die 
during the hard cold winter of martial law professors workers 
priests farmers or aging activists whose names are little known in 
the west they tend to share an intense stubbornness typified by 
another solidarity chant we will win 
solidarity currently is built around of circle of these old 
activists with a sprinkling of new leaders who emerged during two 
waves of strikes last year 
since 1987 the union has had a national executive committee 
chaired by walesa that convenes whenever a major decision is to be 
made it is composed of about 20 members representing regions of 
the country or various constituencies most regions also have 
regional executive commissions made up of representatives of 
factorylevel solidarity committees 
besides its worker base solidarity has a brain trust of 
advisers linked to the former opposition group the committee for 
the defense of workers 
these figures who played a major role in the negotiations that 
have led to reinstating solidarity include historian bronislaw 
geremek essayist adam michnik political theoretician jacek kuron 
and journalist tadeusz mazowiecki 
the national executive committee essentially was picked by 
walesa from activists loyal to him wellknown leaders from 
198081 such as andrzej gwiazda of gdansk or stefan jurczyk of 
szczecin were left off the commission 
a circle of these leaders said in december it had formed a 
working group critical of walesas leadership of the union and 
his willingness to compromise with authorities answering their 
calls for new union elections walesa has promised elections after 
solidarity is legalized 
walesa has also hinted occasionally he would like to relinquish 
solidaritys leadership once the union has been reestablished if 
he were to take the step younger leaders such as zbigniew bujak of 
warsaw wladyslaw frasyniuk of wroclaw or mieczyslaw gil of krakow 
probably would be first in line to take his place 
at the grassroots level the number of factory solidarity 
organizations is growing all the time every day said union 
spokesman wojciech maziarski in warsaw alone he said the union 
knows of factory organizations at 200 workplaces in kielce a 
provincial capital of 200000 people there are 6070 solidarity 
committees in factories 
no one not even solidarity knows how many members it has 
nationwide bujak at a public forum earlier this year estimated the 
figure at about 1 million and walesa told reporters friday that he 
expected it to grow to 5 million to 7 million members 
but it doesnt make sense to talk about current membership 
said maziarski because there is no list 
walesa has said it will be up to the people who join solidarity 
to decide how it will be organized the sejm or parliament meets 
friday to pass the law on trade unions that will enable solidarity 
to be legalized solidarity officials expect it to be registered in 
court next week 
the national executive commission is meeting sunday although 
the purpose of the meeting was not announced in advanced 
presumably the goal will be to draft plans for getting the 
organization functioning smoothly as it drops the vestiges of its 
underground existence 
the national headquarters is expected to be situated in gdansk 
where the union was born after the august 1980 strikes 
as part of its agreement with the government solidarity is to 
be given office space around the country as it had before it was 
banned 
on a factory level solidarity will be obliged to cooperate with 
the official opzz trade unions during negotiations with management 
but the union has made no commitment to cooperate on a regional or 
national level 
both unions say they also expect to compete with each other 
walesa said he would like to see even more competition with 
perhaps a third major union emerging eventually 
with the introduction of freer elections and the prospect of 
opposition representation in the sejm and a new senate solidarity 
will be able to drop some of its responsibility as the main 
opposition force and function solely as a trade union 
solidarity has said it will support independent candidates in 
the election but will not be nominating candidates itself 
instead walesa inaugurated an advisory citizens committee last 
year that draws together representatives of the mainstream 
opposition this group is to bear the brunt of organizing the 
political opposition to the communist party in the june elections 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

