<TEXT>
surgery like youth should not be wasted only on 
the young or at least the elderly should feel free to undergo it 
say researchers who found patients in their 90s tolerate operations 
relatively well 
if surgery truly can improve the quality of your life you 
should not be inhibited by age said dr mark a warner 
coauthor of a study on surgery patients 90 years old and older at 
the mayo clinic in rochester minn 
in the past people were not being operated on purely because 
they were old and people believed they were frail and they would 
not survive the surgery he said in telephone interview thursday 
we were surprised at how well they did and that the rate of 
surgery has increased dramatically in the 90andup age group he 
said 
warner and his colleagues found the 30day survival rate after 
surgery was 916 percent among the 795 patients age 90 and older 
who underwent operations from 1975 through 1985 at the mayo clinic 
a year after their operations 686 percent of the original 
group were still alive and five years later 212 percent 
survived about the same percentage as would be expected to live 
for five years among people the same age who had not had 
operations the researchers said 
these data demonstrate that patients 90 years of age and older 
tolerate the stress of a surgical procedure relatively well the 
researchers said 
what the figures dont show is the major improvement in quality 
of life even if only for a year or two that surgery can provide 
for extremely elderly patients warner said 
for example a 95yearold woman with colon cancer might not be 
considered a good candidate for surgery because of the likelihood 
the malignancy has spread he said 
but forgoing the operation will doom her to bowel obstructions 
that will rob her of her independence and keep her bedridden and 
miserable for the last six months of her life he said 
surgery may well prolong her life two years and though she will 
likely succumb to spreading cancer she will remain much more 
independent and physically comfortable than she would without 
surgery he said 
nationwide surgical procedures are performed almost five times 
as often among 90yearolds and older people as they were 10 years 
ago the researchers reported in fridays journal of the american 
medical association 
as many as 100000 operations may be performed on the 
approximately 1 million americans in that age group this year 
warner said 
the study suggests a dramatic improvement in survival has 
occurred in the last 20 years two decades ago a 71 percent 
survival rate was reported 30 days after surgery in 90yearolds 
and older undergoing similar procedures the doctors said 
although the recent results are not directly comparable to the 
earlier ones the differences are sufficiently striking to 
suggest that better procedures anesthesia and medical care have 
helped improve the survival rate the doctors said 
the most frequently performed procedures in the mayo clinic 
study were repair of broken hips heart pacemaker implants surgery 
on the digestive system prostate operations and hemorrhoid 
procedures he said 
