the head of a delawarebased aerospace company 
says the united states leads japan in developing aircraft wings out 
of nonmetallic composites contradicting one of the claimed 
benefits of the fsx fighter deal 
in my opinion the japanese have the most to gain from the fsx 
program in terms of gaining a total understanding of the complete 
system required to produce an effective composite aircraft 
said james n burns a vice president of hercules inc an 
aerospace company based in wilmington 
burns was one of several executives from the aerospace and 
electronics industry to testify thursday over whether the fsx 
fighter deal with japan amounts to a net technological boon or loss 
for the united states 
the testimony before three house science subcommittees came in 
anticipation of the bush administrations agreement being sent to 
capitol hill shortly 
under the deal st louisbased general dynamics and japans 
mitsubishi heavy industries would codevelop and coproduce the 
fsx an advanced version of the us f16 fighter for deployment 
by japan in the late 1990s 
the deal has prompted criticism that it would amount to a 7 
billion giveaway of valuable american technology likely to be used 
by japan to help propel its own aircraft industry into headtohead 
competition with the united states in the world market 
proponents have argued that the deal would allow the united 
states to benefit from technological advances by the japanese in 
composite wing construction and advanced radar 
composites are tough lightweight materials that utilize carbon 
fiber and epoxy resin in place of metal 
burns told the hearing that successful application of composites 
requires sophisticated computer programs and a detailed array of 
data describing performance of the materials under various 
conditions 
in both areas the united states is obviously well ahead of 
the japanese because of the many aircraft applications in the 
united states which employ carbon fiber composites today he 
said the united states has been the world leader in this field 
indisputably 
john mancini a vice president of the american electronics 
association said the electronics group still has reservations 
about the deal but may be willing to soften its opposition in view 
of encouraging signs from the bush administration that they are 
determined to tighten the agreement 
mancini said the associations board initially had decided to 
oppose the fsx because it felt that the agreement provides no 
real benefit to the american electronics industry and will 
accelerate the japanese as competitors in the world avionics 
arena 
the association represents more than 3500 us companies 
involved with electronics and information technology 
testifying in favor of the fsx was joel l johnson 
international vice president of the aerospace industries 
association of america 
we believe that at this time the fsx deal as negotiated is 
probably about the best agreement that is realistically 
achievable he said we would encourage the us government to 
move forward with the agreement with the proviso that the us 
government should monitor closely the willingness of japan to make 
available technology to the united states 
johnson added we should continue to press the japanese for an 
equitable share of production of the aircraft as well but we do 
not believe that it would be in our interest to encourage the 
japanese to walk away from this agreement and pursue their original 
objective of building a new aircraft without us involvement 
