the agriculture department has sold 5000 
metric tons of surplus butter and butteroil to brazil for 985 
million a fraction of what the government paid for it under the 
dairy price support program 
richard w goldberg acting undersecretary said thursday that 
the 2000 tons of butteroil and 3000 tons of butter were sold by 
the departments commodity credit corp to petrobras comercio 
internacional sainterbras a brazilian state trading company 
deliveries of the surplus products are scheduled through 
september no credit arrangements were involved 
federal laws including last years hunger relief act mandate 
the export sale of 150000 tons of dairy products annually through 
september 1990 so far this fiscal year sales have totaled 15763 
tons goldberg said 
according to a recent report on ccc holdings surplus butter as 
of jan 31 totaled about 155000 metric tons and butteroil 1640 
tons a metric ton is approximately 2205 pounds 
the report showed that ccc had an investment of about 146 per 
pound in the butter and 164 in the oil the price charged to 
brazil was about 84 cents per pound for the butter and 98 cents for 
the butteroil 
sales are made to foreign buyers at approximately the prevailing 
world market prices so as not to undercut other foreign suppliers 
the ccc buys surplus dairy products to support the price of milk 
paid to farmers 
