federal regulators nearing the end of their 
rush effort to seize control of the sickest savings and loans in 
the country have added another 38 to the list of those under 
government control 
the latest takeovers announced thursday were in california 
colorado iowa illinois kansas missouri mississippi and texas 
the actions brought the number of institutions being run by 
federal regulators to 215 in 31 states officials expect to take 
over another 17 institutions within the next few weeks 
the takeovers are being supervised by the federal deposit 
insurance corp which regulates commercial banks the agency began 
the takeover program on feb 7 with the aim of quickly taking 
control of the sickest sampls in order to minimize losses until 
congress appropriates the money to shut them down or sell them to 
new owners 
members of the house banking committee began writing their 
version of the sampl bailout legislation on thursday and were to 
resume consideration of amendments next week 
the fdic said regulatory teams being put into the institutions 
would work to minimize operating losses and ensure that the sampls 
are operated in a safe and sound manner the agency said all the 
institutions will remain open as usual and that all deposits are 
guaranteed up to the 100000 insurance limit 
the largest of the 38 institutions taken over on thursday was 
murray savings association of dallas with assets of 144 billion 
at the end of 1988 
