it would be possible to visit the soviet union in due course a 
buckingham palace statement said 
the announcement came as the soviet leader left windsor castle 
for londons heathrow airport to return home at the end of a 
40hour visit to britain 
earlier gorbachev and his wife raisa drove to the majestic 
castle on the thames river in drizzling rain 
maj nicholas parsons invited the kremlin leader in fluent 
russian to inspect a guard of honor of bearskincapped coldstream 
guards 
the queen in bright pink skirt and cape and her husband 
prince philip greeted her guests on the castle doorstep 
gorbachev was the first soviet leader since 1967 to meet the 
queen and by putting the royal seal on his 40hour visit to 
britain he clearly hoped to enhance the benign image he is trying 
to implant in western minds 
windsor castle the palace 20 miles west of london has been a 
royal residence for more than 800 years and the queen took the 
gorbachevs on a tour of some of its rooms and held a lunch in their 
honor 
the 34 guests including prime minister margaret thatcher and 
her husband denis ate smoked salmon cornets filled with crabmeat 
layers of fillet of beef duck puree and sliced artichoke all 
baked in pastry 
earlier today gorbachev delivered a major televised policy 
speech in the oakpaneled chandeliered splendor of guildhall for 
800 years the seat of london city government 
like many of britains archaic institutions the guildhalls 
power is more in its looks than in its powers like queen elizabeth 
ii the guildhall and its lord mayor are restricted largely to 
ceremonial duties 
the gorbachevs arrived at the guildhall in a 24car motorcade 
through the congested streets of the city londons financial 
district where the lord mayor alderman sir christopher collett 
waited resplendent in black goldbraided robes and threecorner 
hat 
gorbachev was escorted into the building in a procession led by 
the mayor the sergeant at arms and officials bearing a sword and a 
gold mace symbol of city authority 
a trumpet fanfare announced the gorbachevs entry into the hall 
and they stood beside mrs thatcher and her husband denis as the 
soviet and british anthems were played 
an array of dignitaries packed the hall ranging across the 
political spectrum from mrs thatcher through archbishop of 
canterbury robert runcie to bruce kent chairman of the campaign 
for nuclear disarmament 
pikemen musketeers sheriffs and city elders in blue robes 
stood by to complete the pageant 
