<TEXT>
a destructive earthquake seems almost certain 
to strike the eastern united states sometime in the next two 
decades a senate subcommittee was told friday 
while scientists cannot predict when or where the quake might 
hit or its strength they consider one almost sure to occur before 
the year 2010 according to robert l ketter director of the 
national center for earthquake engineering research 
both ketter and sen alan cranston dcalif cited the armenian 
quake in december as raising attention to similar dangers in the 
united states 
quakes in the eastern part of the united states have received 
less attention than those in the west because the strongest eastern 
tremors came before the nation was heavily developed and thus led 
to few losses of lives 
ketter told the subcommittee that while the likelihood of a 
quake in any particular place is low the probability of one 
occurring somewhere in the eastern united states before the year 
2000 can be considered better than 75 percent to 95 percent before 
the year 2010 nearly 100 percent 
the potential for quakes in armenia was also well known yet 
lack of preparation left thousands dead and massive damage 
cranston told the senate subcommittee on science technology and 
space 
the hazard in many parts of the us is no less certain than 
it was in armenia said cranston citing quakes that have caused 
death and major damage in california idaho kentucky alaska and 
other states 
the challenge that faces us now is to use our new capability 
and capacity for earthquake hazards reduction before we have to 
face the public and explain our inaction as the soviets now 
must cranston said 
the senators comments came in support of a bill to strengthen 
the national earthquake hazards program including a transfer of 
that activity to the us geological survey currently the 
earthquake program is part of the federal emergency management 
agency 
cranston noted that earthquakes once thought of as primarily a 
california and alaska problem are now known to be a major danger 
to many states 
perhaps the most powerful quake ever to strike the united states 
occurred in a series of tremors in 18111812 that rocked the new 
madrid mo region ketter testified 
in addition severe quakes in the 18th century and 19th century 
struck charleston sc boston under the ocean near new york 
city and in the charlevoix region of quebec ketter told the 
subcommittee 
compounding the problem is the fact that in the eastern states 
underlying rocks are older and more dense thus reported ketter 
earthquakes in the east can cause damage over a much larger area 
than in the west 
one of the 1811 quakes in missouri for example had a strength 
similar to the 1906 san francisco quake the temblor in missouri 
however affected an area 15 times larger than the california quake 
lacy e suiter chairman of the central us earthquake 
consotrium testified that there is a 40 percent to 63 percent 
chance of a strong quake occurring in the ned madrid mo region 
by the turn of the century 
ketter said that if the 18111812 missouri quakes were to occur 
today the death toll could approach 5000 people with massive 
destruction in such communities as memphis tenn paducah ky 
carbondale ill evansville ind poplar bluff mo and little 
rock ark 
