<TEXT>
the american museum of natural history announced 
friday it would not give a 150yearold indian relic to a cree 
indian who ran across the country to retrieve it saying he wanted 
the sacred object for his people 
spokesman herbert kurz said the museum sent jim thunder an 
express mail letter to his home in edmonton canada on thursday 
notifying him of the decision 
i had been anticipating this thunder said he would not say 
if he would continue his effort to retrieve the artifact and said 
he had no further comment 
on sept 1 in edmonton the 38yearold american indian began a 
2700mile run across canada to draw attention to his mission he 
arrived march 21 in new york and formally made his request to 
museum officials the next day 
thunder claimed to be a greatgreat grandson of chief big bear 
the cree leader who created the artifact a sacred calicowrapped 
bundle holding bear claws sweet grass and a plug of tobacco to 
give his people spiritual strength and guidance 
ten years ago thunder said big bear spoke to him in dreams and 
visions and instructed him to bring the sacred bundle back to his 
tribe in western canada where it would be used in prayers and 
sacred indian ceremonies 
in 1934 a son of big bear gave the bundle to a museum 
anthropologist 
since that time it has been stored as part of a special research 
collection while it is available for study by scholars and 
indians it has never been put on display 
stanley a freed a museum curator who met with thunder told 
him in the letter that several factors including claims for the 
bundle by other cree went into the museums decision 
the museum has received communications from other cree 
asking that the medicine bundle not be given to mr thunder and 
raising questions about his relationship to big bear kurz said 
other indians and tribal groups have told the museum that the 
bundle should be given to them rather than to thunder 
thunder admits he has no blood relationship with big bear 
but said he was adopted in 1985 by a greatgranddaughter of the 
leader 
big bear made the bundle more than 150 years ago when he was 
about 13 years old and later wore it into battle for protection 
and guidance 
a son of big bear joe pimi who was also known as horse child 
sought out the museum anthropologist who was leading an 
expedition into central canada and presented it to the museum for 
safekeeping the museum said 
it is our responsibility to honor pimis wish freed wrote 
to thunder 
