not have a major impact on soviet capability to wage nuclear war 
although gorbachev said arms control would stall unless the west 
dropped plans to modernize its shortrange nuclear missiles mrs 
thatcher said her belief in a nuclear deterrent remains firm 
gorbachev insisted nato had an advantage over the warsaw pact in 
every area but tanks and said in short fears of the soviet 
military threat are groundless 
mrs thatcher said east bloc forces still outnumber the western 
alliance 21 
on a happier note she said the queen gave a very definite 
yes to the invitation extended during gorbachevs lunch with 
elizabeth at windsor palace 
no date was set for the visit the first by a british monarch 
since the bolshevik revolution of 1917 czar nicholas ii who was 
killed with his family by the communists was a cousin of the 
queens grandfather 
gorbachev and his wife raisa spent 40 hours in britain before 
flying home and ending a sixday journey that also took them to 
ireland and cuba 
in londons guildhall the 1000yearold seat of city 
government gorbachev rubbed shoulders with robed bewigged 
notables marched behind the ceremonial macebearer and generally 
seemed to enjoy his encounter with traditional british pageantry 
then with mrs thatcher seated before him he delivered an 
unusually brief 27minute speech 
he said the soviet union would halt production this year of 
weaponsgrade uranium and will shut down two more reactors that 
produce plutonium for nuclear weapons by the end of next year 
he called it another major step toward the complete cessation 
of production of fissionable materials for use in weapons 
later friday soviet foreign ministry spokesman gennady i 
gerasimov refused to say at a briefing which reactors would be 
closed or give their locations 
the defense department official who refused to be further 
identified said they the soviets have weapons material coming 
out of medium and shortrange missiles there has been as 
assessment that they have stockpiles of weaponsgrade materials 
if the soviets shut down weapons reactors for several years 
they could restart them later when the military begins to run low 
of weapons material 
gorbachevs statement did not provide adequate information for 
pentagon analysts to assess what impact the steps would have on 
producing plutunium and tritium the two materials needed for 
modern thermonuclear weapons gorbachev did not mention tritium 
it was one of several recent pronouncements by gorbachev about 
arms reduction in december he announced to the united nations the 
soviet union soon would begin reducing its standing army by 500000 
men and withdrawing troops and tanks from europe and the chinese 
frontier 
he praised britain for unilaterally discarding chemical weapons 
and said his country recently completed a facility which british 
experts would be invited to inspect for destroying its own stocks 
the hitherto secret soviet defense budget will be published he 
said 
reviewing his plan to reform soviet society gorbachev 
acknowledged he initially had not realized the magnitude of the 
task 
in an apparent attempt to reassure westerners who fear a 
conservative backlash he said there is no turning back for 
anyone the people have firmly linked their destiny with 
perestroika 
gorbachev got a standing ovation and a resounding endorsement by 
mrs thatcher we want you to succeed in your task she said in 
her reply and promised to help in practical ways too where our 
help is sought and desired 
at a news conference later the prime minister said she found 
gorbachev as dynamic determined stimulating and confident as 
ever 
she has met him five times three of them on visits he has made 
to britain 
recalling the first encounter when he came to britain in 1984 
as no 2 man in the kremlin she said some years ago i think i 
said i thought mr gorbachev was a man i could do business with i 
might just repeat today that i think that he is a person with whom 
i look forward to doing more business 
both sides acknowledged the talks were tough argumentative and 
yielded little practical progress but the visit was a public 
relations triumph for gorbachev 
after the speech he walked into admiring crowds for the second 
time on the trip and his televised appearance with the queen 
guaranteed him new prestige with the royaltyloving british public 
the 63yearold monarch in a bright pink cape and skirt led 
the gorbachevs around windsor castle a royal residence for 800 
years before lunch with her husband prince philip her son 
edward mrs thatcher and 33 other guests 
gorbachev later arrived home in moscow the official tass news 
agency reported friday night without giving details 
