the government friday moved to abolish labor 
regulations that guarantee dockworkers jobs for life prompting 
strikes by thousands of employees at five big british ports 
including liverpool and tilbury 
one union leader warned abolition of 42yearold national dock 
labor scheme may provoke a nationwide strike 
the leftistled transport and general workers union which 
called the walkout urged its members to return to work ahead of a 
meeting scheduled monday to discuss whether to hold a ballot on an 
official strike 
in the house of commons prime minister margaret thatchers 
government put forward legislation to scrap the regulations by 
july they apply to 9400 dockworkers at 46 ports handling 70 
percent of britains foreign trade 
the government plans to pay compensation of up to 59500 to 
each of the 1000 dockworkers expected to lose their jobs when the 
system is abolished 
the legislation welcomed by employers is certain to be passed 
because of mrs thatchers big majority in the commons 
on thursday employment secretary norman fowler called the dock 
labor regulations an anachronism amid jeers from opposition 
labor party legislators 
as long as the scheme continues to operate it will remain the 
biggest obstacle to a modern and efficient ports industry said 
fowler 
more than 2200 dockworkers at liverpool in northwestern 
england and the east coast port of tilbury two of britains 
biggest ports walked out after mass meetings friday another 
english port southampton was at a standstill and smaller 
walkouts disrupted bristol the scottish port of glasgow 
the labor party accused the government of an act of wilful 
sabotage 
the dock labor regulations introduced by a labor government 
stipulate that manning levels can be cut only when workers quit 
voluntarily if a port goes out of business dockworkers covered by 
the system must be hired at another port 
the regulations were introduced to stop harsh employment 
conditions when dockers were hired on a daytoday basis competed 
with each other for work and had no job benefits but critics say 
abuses have grown and some dockworkers get paid not to work 
