<TEXT>
the past has come alive in hungary 
where people are striding into a future they hope will spell 
democracy 
they sit on park benches reading about imre nagy the hitherto 
disgraced leader of the 1956 antisoviet uprising that was crushed 
by soviet tanks three new books on nagy sell rapidly at stores and 
street stalls 
an old coat of arms abolished by the communists in 1948 has 
become a symbol of national pride parliament has joined the 
discussion on possibly restoring it as the national emblem 
the wave of nostalgia peaked march 15 when an estimated 100000 
people turned out to mark the anniversary of a failed revolt in 
1848 against austrian hapsburg rule 
it became clear then that the preoccupation with the past has 
everything to do with the future 
the aims of both the 1848 and 1956 revolts and reforms today are 
the same constitutional democracy and national independence 
miklos tamasgaspar one of the leaders of the many new independent 
political groups told the crowd 
hungarians are well aware of their past failures in trying now 
to achieve those goals diplomats call it a healthy pessimism 
but others fear the dash for reform could end in disaster 
they speculate about armed action by the military or oldguard 
communists who have also organized their own groups in recent 
months and despite the new leeway from moscow they are still 
mindful of the bloodshed that ended reform in 1956 
the cart cant go backwards but it can overturn the 
reformist politburo member reszoe nyers said in a recent radio 
interview 
even hungarians most active in creating the change cannot 
explain how it happened so fast and hesitate to predict how it will 
continue 
yet both the communist leadership and the founders of 
independent movements recognize they can only achieve lasting 
change by working together 
with the memory of 1956 still sharp both sides are wary of each 
other both have much to lose the communists their power and the 
independent groups their chance to bring change 
but hungarians know the new climate in moscow means the time for 
change is now or never as a banner at the march 15 rally said 
on recent visits to the kremlin communist party leader karoly 
grosz and premier miklos nemeth came home with what they said was 
an ok from president mikhail s gorbachev to go ahead with reform 
including political pluralism 
the first test will be the 1990 parliamentary elections whose 
form is still unclear 
in some respects the march 15 rally was the start of 
campaigning for those elections the independent groups showed they 
have become a force drawing far larger crowds than those at a 
communist rally 
there seems to be vague agreement on all sides however that 
completely free elections will not be possible by 1990 and that 
some provisional arrangement should be made to get the independents 
into parliament so they can help lay the groundwork for completely 
open elections in 1995 
for the independents it is essential to maintain unity both 
within their own ranks and against the communists 
unity is most important in the face of the monolithic power 
which is still in place said rudolf joo a leading member of the 
hungarian democratic forum one of the most influential and broadly 
based groups 
ferenc koeszeg a leading member of the league of free 
democrats says it is important for the independent groups to work 
out a common position before negotiating with the communists who 
opened tentative talks with each group in february 
another problem for the independents with their largely 
intellectual base in budapest is to attract support from workers 
who are increasingly unhappy with price increases and 
governmentimposed austerity measures 
the communists have published their own action program 
committing themselves to a multiparty system free elections and 
representational democracy 
the communist party is playing a role as if it were one of the 
independent groups said the free democrats koeszeg with 
the action program they are trying to occupy the place of an 
opposition group 
communist leaders say they would in fact be willing to go into 
opposition but emphasize they are confident of at least 51 percent 
of the vote in the elections 
the partys confidence stems from its 40 years of political 
experience and control of the media while the independent groups 
are just getting started 
in a oneparty system the party has a monopoly of peoples 
thinking and even their souls said sandor csoori a poet and a 
forum leader 
</TEXT>
