<DOCNO> AP890407-0276 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when they talk about the economic outlook these 
days many wall street analysts use a term coined in the 1970s but 
not heard much since then stagflation 
the word a hybrid of stagnation and inflation describes an 
unpleasant set of circumstances once believed to be nearly 
impossible 
in a period of stagflation economic growth is weak at best but 
inflation keeps running at the kind of rapid pace that is supposed 
to occur only in times of strong expansion 
that condition prevailed for extended periods in the 70s amid a 
series of unusual influences including a runaway rise in world oil 
prices and a couple of long and severe recessions 
the precise causes of stagflation in those days are still being 
debated but lately a more urgent question has been raised after a 
decade of strong growth and relatively low inflation is 
stagflation coming back 
most analysts believe that growth of economic activity has begun 
to slow since early this year under the influence of a sustained 
period of credittightening by the federal reserve 
shortterm interest rates at 9 percentplus stand more than 3 
percentage points higher than they were a year ago that means that 
for many borrowers the cost of money has been increased by about 50 
percent 
yet some gauges of inflationary pressures have increased 
suggesting that the cost of living is now rising at an annual rate 
in the 5 percent to 6 percent range 
despite those symptoms however most observers dont believe 
the economy is about to come down with a sustained case of 
stagflation 
recent signs of slower economic growth and an escalation of 
inflation are typical for this stage of a business cycle 
maintains jack lavery research chief at merrill lynch amp co the 
conditions for a prolonged period of stagflation appear to be 
absent 
we expect economic growth to slow on balance for the rest of 
the year the momentum of inflation should start to abate shortly 
after the economy weakens 
wright investors service inc which recently lowered its 
estimates for economic growth and corporate profits through 1990 
takes a similar view 
inflation is probably now close to its peak rate for the 
current business cycle say analysts at the bridgeport conn 
money management firm 
by next year wright says inflation is likely to set no more 
than a 4 percent annual pace even lower if the economy falls 
into a genuine recession 
at nomura securities international inc economists david resler 
and carol stone declare we attach a small probability to the 
stagflation scenario 
at its heart stagflation pertains to an environment where the 
costs of essential production inputs are rising rapidly and 
retarding productivity 
in the 1970s that condition was first triggered by the 1973 
oil embargo though oil prices have risen recently a replay of 
anything like those earlier episodes seems improbable 
a brief period of rising inflation and falling economic growth 
is more likely reduced growth may be necessary to alleviate 
strains on production capacity 
but that also eases inflationary pressures so the conditions 
of stagflation should be shortlived 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

