<TEXT>
inflation fears drove up interest rates and 
depressed most of the credit markets during the first quarter but 
threemonth treasury bills and junk bonds stood out among the pack 
analysts say 
a quarterly analysis by moodys investors service inc released 
this past week found that highyield highrisk junk bonds had 
the best rate of return in the januarymarch period roughly 22 
percent 
threemonth tbills had almost as good a return 21 percent 
return 
but junk bonds contain a risk of default that must be factored 
in when considering their return said john lonski a senior 
economist with the securitiesrating firm 
one would have to say that the superior performance adjusted 
for risk unquestionably belonged to the threemonth treasury 
bill lonski said 
by comparison investmentgrade corporate bonds provided a 
return of about 14 percent and longterm treasuries those of 
730 years maturity 11 percent 
a separate index of government and corporate bonds compiled by 
shearson lehman hutton inc showed a total return of 11 percent in 
the quarter 
the rate of return includes accrued interest plus any capital 
gains through price increases 
investors that fared best during the quarter followed a 
socalled barbell strategy which calls for concentrating 
investments on the two extremes of the spectrum shortterm bills 
and longterm bonds according to james l kochan chief 
fixedincome strategist for merrill lynch capital markets 
the plan paid off during the first quarter because shortterm 
rates jumped while prices of longterm bonds held up fairly well 
he said 
threemonth treasury bills yielded 839 percent on jan 3 the 
first trading day of the year on march 31 they yielded 918 
percent 
the 30year treasury yielded 908 percent on jan 3 and 909 
percent on march 31 though it fluctuated many times due to 
economic news that jolted the market 
prices and yields on bonds move in opposite directions so a 
high yield means a low price 
the situation in which the yield on the threemonth tbill 
surpasses the 30year treasury bonds yield is what wall street 
calls an inverted yield curve 
the yield curve which illustrates the difference between 
shortand longterm interest rates normally slopes upward to the 
right with longermaturing issues yielding more than shorter 
issues to reflect the risk of keeping money tied up 
but shortterm rates rose during the quarter amid concerns that 
worsening inflation which erodes the value of fixedincome 
securities would lead to further credit tightening by the federal 
reserve 
an inverted yield curve is sometimes viewed as an early warning 
of a recession because it means shorter rates have risen so high 
that they could choke off economic growth 
the inflation news during the first quarter brought concern 
among the credit markets the government reported that wholesale 
prices rose 1 percent in january and february 
since then several other governmentissued economic reports 
have indicated the economy might be slowing easing fears of 
inflation and adding a lift to the credit markets 
prices of longterm bonds have risen back to the range 
prevailing before the march 17 figures indicating a high degree of 
resiliency in the bond market kochan said 
its extraordinary really its probably performing better 
than any of us had any right to expect said kochan 
