<TEXT>
attempts to produce lowtech nuclear fusion which 
electrified the scientific world when announced two weeks ago have 
produced no cries of success and at least one apparent failure 
a university of utah scientist and a british colleague touched 
off a scramble when they described creating nuclear fusion in a jar 
of heavy water they said the process generated four times more 
power than it used 
if true their technique could revolutionize power production 
yielding a steady supply of cheap clean electricity but neither 
they nor anyone else has offered a convincing explanation of the 
principles of physics involved 
at massachusetts institute of technology chemist mark s 
wrighton said he obtained technical details from university of utah 
officials and started a duplicate experiment it has been going 
continuously since march 27 with no evidence of nuclear fusion he 
said thursday 
spokesmen at the lawrence livermore national laboratory in 
livermore cal and the los alamos national laboratory in los 
alamos nm said their attempts at duplicating the work have not 
produced conclusive results 
wrighton said he was very skeptical of the utah claim as 
was john deutch mits provost 
it would be terrific if its true but i dont think its 
true deutch said 
wrighton said his lack of results could mean that the technique 
does not work but it could also mean that the fusion is so slight 
that it cannot be detected or the reaction may need more time to 
occur 
the fusion feat was announced at a news conference by b stanley 
pons of utah and martin fleischmann of the university of 
southampton in england they claimed to have achieved nuclear 
fusion at room temperature with equipment available in any college 
lab 
late last week wrighton and several other research groups 
around the country received copies of the teams scientific paper 
which he said confirmed that he had been doing the experiment just 
as they had 
we see no physical basis at the moment for thinking that 
nuclear fusion is going to occur wrighton said and we 
certainly have no evidence that theres a big effect one that 
would have technological consequences in the near term 
pons was in meetings all day thursday and could not be reached 
for comment on the mit experiment his office said university of 
utah spokeswoman pamela fogle noted that pons and fleischmann 
believe the reaction can take 10 days to three weeks to occur 
on thursday researchers from the los alamos laboratory met with 
pons to discuss his research the deseret news in salt lake city 
reported 
utah legislators were to meet today in special session to 
consider allocating 5 million to develop and commercialize fusion 
research however the state board of regents says the funds should 
be used only when the fusion research is confirmed 
the researchers paper has been published in the netherlands in 
the journal of electroanalytical chemistry 
we realize that the results reported here raise more questions 
than they provide answers and that much further work is required on 
this topic they wrote 
wrighton said some attempts to duplicate the work began even 
before the university of utah news conference as word of the 
discovery began to leak out 
we understand through the grapevine that the groups going that 
long havent seen any confirmation of the essential claims 
either he said 
last week steven jones of brigham young university said he had 
independently performed a similar experiment last year but obtained 
far less impressive output than the utah team 
scientists at the brookhaven national laboratory in upton ny 
have tried to duplicate jones approach in two experiments one 
produced nothing and the other turned up results too small to be 
statistically meaningful spokeswoman mona rowe said thursday 
fusion is the energy source that powers the sun and hydrogen 
bombs the energy produced by nuclear power plants comes from 
fission which splits atoms during fusion they are joined 
together 
ordinarily fusion requires hundreds of millions of degrees of 
heat but pons and fleischmann said they produced fusion energy in 
a 6inch glass jar at room temperature and normal pressure their 
equipment included a sixvolt battery rods of the precious metal 
palladium and heavy water or water with deuterium 
