<TEXT>
the nuclear regulatory commission today 
approved the drastic streamlining of its procedure for the 
licensing of nuclear power plants that the commissions chairman 
said could halve the current time needed to build a plant 
however chairman lando zech said he knew of no company 
interested in building a new nuclear plant no one has ordered a 
plant since 1978 and the oldest active order was placed in 1974 
the new process provides for advance approval of possible sites 
and standard plant designs and combines most of the current 
construction and operating licenses into a single license to be 
issued only after all safety issues have been resolved in 
preconstruction proceedings 
currently many issues such as evacuation planning are left 
until the operating license usually not considered until the plant 
is complete 
recent plants have taken an average of 13 years to complete 
some of that delay has resulted from suspension of construction at 
some plants for financial reasons 
after a unanimous vote by the commission to approve the new 
licensing procedure zech told reporters we should be able to 
build a plant in six years or less in this country 
the commission has long wanted a more streamlined licensing 
procedure but has been unable to persuade congress to enact one 
without new legislation the commission must still hold two 
hearings one on whether to grant the combined construction and 
operating license and the second on whether all the license 
conditions have been met 
zech said he believed the new regulations had narrowed the range 
of issues to be considered at the second hearing so much that 
legislation would not be necessary 
many analysts have pointed to the proliferation of reactor 
designs as an impediment to management training maintenance and 
construction the nations 110 licensed plants and 11 under 
construction encompass more than 60 designs 
zech said general electric corp westinghouse corp combustion 
engineering inc and the electric power research institute all have 
asked the commission staff to review versions of a current plant 
design for possible licensing 
