<TEXT>
companies ranging from fastfood giant 
mcdonalds corp to aircraft maker grumman corp agree they need to 
attract older workers to stave off an impending labor shortage as 
baby boomers age 
there is really no choice daniel e knowles vice president 
for human resources and planning at grumman told a national 
council on the aging seminar in new orleans recently if were 
going to increase productivity and meet the needs of an aging 
workforce were going to have to totally change the concept of 
retirement 
statisticians say the average age is rising in this country 
people in the baby boom generation have had fewer children than 
their parents and have waited longer to have children while 
medical advances have kept their parents alive longer 
meanwhile the number of people available to take jobs has 
tightened said philip rones of the bureau of labor standards 
we have 3 million fewer younger workers than we did 10 years 
ago said rones were in the middle of the nations longest 
peacetime expansion unemployment is at a 15year low 
the dearth of teenagers coupled with a tight labor market has 
prompted mcdonalds to look for older people to work as everything 
from burgerflipper to managers for its fastfood restaurants 
we recruit from our customers said stanley stein a senior 
vice president at mcdonalds corp in oak brook ill we use tray 
liners counter cards brochures 
mcdonalds emphasizes that older workers can set their own hours 
and wont work enough hours to lose social security benefits said 
stein 
participants in the conference agreed that the possible loss of 
social security or pension benefits is one of the biggest obstacles 
to keeping older workers 
when travelers insurance co set up a job bank for its own 
retired workers it also had to change restrictions that kept 
workers from collecting their pensions if they continued to work 
harold johnson former personnel director for travelers and now 
senior vice president of a company that trains executives said 
retirees can work 1000 hours a year the equivalent of six months 
without affecting their pension 
travelers calls them when it needs a temporary worker and at 
least half of the 1000 or so temporaries called in each day are 
retired from the company said johnson 
he said travelers also eliminated its mandatory retirement age 
and set up a plan for workers who wanted to continue working 
parttime rather than fulltime after the age of 65 
not every company or even a majority is worried about a 
labor shortage or looking toward older people as its solution said 
participants at the conference 
for every company that does dozens and dozens arent said 
johnson downsizing is a fact of life in american industry and 
older employees are the most affected and dozens of dozens of 
companies are still laboring under the myths that we have blown 
away 
the myths include beliefs that a workers ability deteriorates 
with age and that older workers will cost a company more in sick 
leave and medical benefits than their work is worth said 
conference participants 
laura myers mccoy a spokeswoman for days inns of america inc 
said her companys elderly workers not only have a better 
attendance rate than their younger counterparts but stay longer 
she said the corporate headquarters in atlanta loses an average of 
40 percent of its reservation agents every year 
the turnover rate among the older workers at our corporate 
office is less than 1 percent she said 
knowles said grummans highly trained workforce has always 
tended to be older than average something which itself refutes 
the belief that a younger worker is a better worker 
when we put a man on the moon 20 years ago we made the lunar 
module he said our past president told me it wasnt a bunch 
of kids who put a man on the moon it was a bunch of middleaged 
and older workers 
that wasnt a putdown of kids it was just a positive 
statement acknowledging the long services of the older guys and 
that all that service and smarts made the place tick 
knowles said the average age at grumman rose from 37 to 45 
between 1970 and 1977 when a decreasing market forced 13600 
layoffs rather than age or seniority he said the layoffs were 
based on each departments ranking of its workers from best to 
worst 
end adv for monday april 10 
