<TEXT>
the casino control commission voted 
unanimously friday to reject a bid by elsinores atlantis casino 
hotel to stay in business despite deep financial trouble the 
firstever denial of a license renewal in new jerseys decadelong 
casino history 
commission chairman walter read said elsinore shore associates 
the casino owners failed in their twoweek hearing to demonstrate 
that they could remain financially viable to merit an extension of 
their current license which expires next friday 
five hours after the 50 vote the commission took another 
unprecedented step and appointed a state conservator to run the 
atlantis until it can be sold 
the move at least temporarily ensured that the casino would stay 
open and the 2100 employees would keep their jobs despite the 
license expiration on april 14 
read referring to testimony by elsinore vice president bruce 
mckee scolded the company for shoddy operations and dubious 
financial projections 
mr mckee said that he would prefer not to call the licensee a 
seat of the pants operation read said before moving for the 
license denial but it is clear from figures regarding cash 
position and overdue payables that it is precisely that 
the casino which emerged from bankruptcy reorganization last 
september has posted losses each of the last four years including 
a whopping 75 million in 1988 it also has failed consistently to 
meet the financial projections upon which its previous license 
renewals were based read noted 
elsinore president jeanne hood said she was overwhelmed by 
the commission action she collected more than 352000 in salary 
and bonuses last year and the casinos past due bills approached 
2 million ms hood said she was most anxious to keep the 
atlantis open for the sake of the employees 
elsinore admitted during the hearing it could not show the 
financial wherewithal to stay in business and meet state standards 
for the entire twoyear license period instead the companys 
lawyers asked the commission to be flexible and let the casino stay 
in business long enough to sell out 
but read said to do so would compromise the credibility of the 
states vigorous casino regulations and heighten the risk of 
unethical conduct by the casinos strapped management read cited 
testimony by mckee acknowledging that the casino on occasion failed 
to maintain the staterequired minimum in its reserve to pay off 
winnings 
the conclusion is inescapable that if we were to grant 
relicensure these standards would be rendered meaningless read 
said 
anthony parrillo director of the division of gaming 
enforcement called it a somber day for the casino but hailed 
the denial as the right move for the health of new jerseys gaming 
industry 
if the case shows anything it shows that regulatory 
credentials have to predominate over economic consequences he 
said 
the commissioners admitted the conservator issue was unexplored 
territory fraught with hazards and despite the 41 vote for 
conservatorship the commissioners delayed until next week the 
decision of who the conservator would be and what powers one would 
possess it was unclear how the arrangement would affect efforts to 
sell the casino 
there are so many questions that have to be answered it could 
really be a fiscal minefield commissioner frank dodd the lone 
dissenter told reporters earlier in the day he said it might be 
preferable to padlock the casino 
another possible outcome is protection from the bankruptcy 
court where elsinore first turned in 1985 
company lawyers earlier in the week urged a federal bankruptcy 
court in camden to intervene and keep the atlantis in business the 
judge declined immediate action but agreed to consider the matter 
next tuesday 
in the commission hearing elsinore claimed the best hopes for 
the casinos creditors rested with a decision to keep the casino 
open under the current ownership the casino said any chance of 
fetching a fair selling price would be spoiled by a closing or 
appointment of a conservator 
mrs hood testified earlier in the week that several prospective 
buyers have surfaced and that a sale likely could be completed in 
coming months 
