the pittston co said it continued to 
operate most of its virginia and west virginia coal mines thursday 
the first full day of a strike by 1400 members of the united mine 
workers union 
pittston co spokeswoman susan copeland said that the company 
would not release details about which facilities were working 
we are operating most of them copeland said theyre not 
all up to par but they will be but we wont be outlining which 
operations we are operating and which we are not 
the umw said members of 22 local unions were called out on 
strike at 4 pm wednesday pittston operations in kentucky and 
some small operations in virginia and west virginia were not 
included in the work stoppage umw spokesman joe corcoran said that 
may change 
some 1700 miners in the three states have been working without 
a contract for 14 months since the 1984 national agreement expired 
on jan 31 1988 
corcoran said the union would like pittston to reconsider its 
plan to bring in replacements for the strikers he said he was not 
hopeful that they would 
its very easy to take advantage of the unemployment in 
appalachia corcoran said it seems theyd just as soon pit an 
unemployed miner against another miner on strike they dont care 
negotiations are due to resume in washington next week 
according to corcoran talks that had been scheduled for thursday 
and friday of this week were postponed at the companys request he 
said 
